-- CareerFlow dummy/demo data seed script (bulk version — scale to any size)
-- Run this in pgAdmin's Query Tool against the target database.
-- Replace the email below with the account you want the data attached to.
--
-- Company logos in the UI are resolved live from each company's `website`
-- via Google's favicon service, so only *real, resolvable* domains produce a
-- logo. This script therefore uses two tiers of companies:
--   1) 1499 real, distinct companies with real domains -> real logos
--      (225 original + 486 batch-1 + 788 batch-2, hand-verified, dedup'd
--      against each other — spans big tech, fintech, e-commerce, retail,
--      banking, insurance, pharma/biotech, energy/utilities, airlines,
--      hospitality, logistics/shipping, automotive/auto-parts, semis,
--      chemicals, mining/steel, telecom, media/entertainment, gaming,
--      SaaS/dev-tools/AI, IT services/consulting, and Indian/Chinese/
--      Japanese/Korean/SEA/European companies across all of the above).
--   2) Procedurally-generated but realistic-sounding fictional companies
--      (e.g. "Northbridge Analytics") with NO website set, so the UI's
--      existing colored-initials fallback renders instead of a broken
--      image. This keeps every name human-readable — no "Company #123"
--      hash suffixes anywhere (companies, recruiters, or referrals).
--
-- To scale the dataset up or down, just edit the N_FICTIONAL_COMPANIES,
-- N_RECRUITERS, and N_REFERRALS constants below (search "Row-count knobs").
-- Every real company always keeps its real, resolvable domain regardless of
-- how large N_FICTIONAL_COMPANIES is — only the fictional tier grows.
--   e.g. N_FICTIONAL_COMPANIES := 501   -> 2000 total companies
--        N_FICTIONAL_COMPANIES := 2501  -> 4000 total companies
--        N_FICTIONAL_COMPANIES := 4501  -> 6000 total companies
-- (fictional name-space supports up to 40*10*20 = 8000 unique combos, so
-- keep N_FICTIONAL_COMPANIES at or below 8000.)
--
-- Recruiter/referrer names are built by combining 50 first names x 50 last
-- names (2500 possible combos), which is enough to give every recruiter and
-- referral a distinct, natural-looking name with no visible numbering —
-- bump N_RECRUITERS/N_REFERRALS past 2500 and names start repeating (still
-- fine, just no longer guaranteed unique per row).
--
-- Historical spread: every table's created_at/updated_at (and companies'
-- created_at, job_applications' application_date, interviews'
-- scheduled_at, recruiters' last_contacted_at, referrals' requested_date)
-- is scattered pseudo-randomly across roughly the past 2-4 years using a
-- prime-multiplier-mod trick (e.g. `(i * 137) % 730`), instead of clustering
-- everything in the last few minutes/days. This gives trend charts (e.g.
-- applications-per-month, funnel-over-time) real month-to-month and
-- year-over-year variation instead of one giant spike near "now". Follow-up
-- due dates are intentionally kept near-term (+/- a couple months of today)
-- since they represent live reminders, not historical events.
--
-- Real-companies-first ordering: the Companies list defaults to sorting by
-- created_at DESC (newest first) in both the API and the UI. So real
-- companies (with logos) are deliberately dated within the last 0-365 days,
-- while fictional companies (no logo) are dated 366-1460 days ago -- this
-- guarantees every real company sorts above every fictional one under the
-- default sort, without requiring the user to touch the sort dropdown.

DO $$
DECLARE
    v_user_id BIGINT;
    v_company_ids BIGINT[] := ARRAY[]::BIGINT[];
    v_app_ids BIGINT[] := ARRAY[]::BIGINT[];
    v_recruiter_ids BIGINT[] := ARRAY[]::BIGINT[];
    v_referral_ids BIGINT[] := ARRAY[]::BIGINT[];
    v_new_id BIGINT;

    -- ── Row-count knobs ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    -- Bump these to scale the whole dataset. Total companies = 1499 (real) +
    -- N_FICTIONAL_COMPANIES. See header comment above for target presets.
    N_FICTIONAL_COMPANIES CONSTANT INT := 4501; -- + 1499 real = 6000 companies
    N_RECRUITERS CONSTANT INT := 5000;          -- unique-ish recruiter contacts
    N_REFERRALS  CONSTANT INT := 5000;          -- unique-ish referral requests
    -- job_applications end up ~5-18x per real company + ~2-6x per fictional
    -- company (tens of thousands of rows total)
    -- interviews end up ~roughly half of job_applications (2-3 rounds each)
    -- follow_ups = 1 per job_application

    -- 225 real, globally recognizable companies with real domains so the
    -- app's favicon-based logos resolve correctly.
